&lt;li&gt;Run the full design arc: pull signal from research, sketch and prototype (using whatever tools make sense, including AI-assisted ones), run tight reviews, hand off specs engineers can build from, and stay involved through launch.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Show up in roadmap and strategy conversations with Product. Contribute a vision and strong point of view on how we get there.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Partner with Engineering, Product, and Marketing so the product feels like one brand&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build the boring-but-important stuff: how critique works, how the design system evolves, how we reuse patterns, how we review AI-assisted work so it still meets our bar.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Say no when something isn’t ready. That includes experiences that need clearer disclosure, better fallbacks, or a simpler path before customers see them.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strong data-informed product thinking: ability to leverage quantitative data, behavioral insights, experimentation results, and customer signals to inform design decisions, identify opportunities, and continuously improve the user experience.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
